ude/skills/write-tests/SKILL.md` — content outline\n\nFrontmatter:\n- `name: write-tests`\n- `description: Use when writing new tests, refactoring existing tests, or designing a test strategy. Applies industry-standard principles: AAA structure, FIRST traits, test pyramid, behavior-over-implementation, edge-case coverage. Language-agnostic.`\n\nBody sections:\n1. **When to use** — writing new tests, refactoring brittle ones, planning coverage for a feature.\n2. **Core principles**\n   - **AAA**: Arrange / Act / Assert — visually separated.\n   - **FIRST**: Fast, Independent, Repeatable, Self-validating, Timely.\n   - **Test the behavior, not the implementation** — assert on observable outputs and side effects, not internal calls.\n   - **One logical assertion per test** — multiple `expect`s are fine if they verify one concept.\n   - **Test pyramid** — many unit, fewer integration, very few e2e.\n3. **Naming** — `should_<expected>_when_<condition>` or `given_<state>_when_<action>_then_<outcome>`. Test names describe behavior, not method names.\n4. **What to cover** — happy path, boundary values, empty/null/zero, error paths, idempotency, concurrency where relevant.\n5. **Mocks & doubles** — mock at architectural boundaries (network, DB, clock, filesystem); never mock the system under test. Prefer fakes over mocks where feasible.\n6. **Anti-patterns to flag** — shared mutable state between tests, sleeps for synchronization, asserting on log output, snapshot tests with no review discipline, tests that pass when the code is deleted.\n7. **Coverage** — coverage is a leading indicator, not a goal. Mutation testing > line coverage when available.\n8. **Checklist** — short bullet list to run through before declaring tests done.\n\n## `.claude/skills/code-review/SKILL.md` — content outline\n\nFrontmatter:\n- `name: code-review`\n- `description: Use before committing or opening a PR. Reviews changed code for correctness, readability, SOLID adherence, error handling at boundaries, common security smells (injection, secrets, missing auth checks), performance pitfalls, and scope discipline. Language-agnostic.`\n\nBody sections:\n1. **When to use** — pre-commit self-review, reviewing a teammate's diff, sanity check before opening a PR.\n2. **Review order** (most-impactful first)\n   1. **Correctness** — does it actually solve the stated problem? Are edge cases handled?\n   2. **Scope** — does the diff do one thing? Flag drive-by refactors.\n   3. **Design** — SOLID, separation of concerns, no premature abstraction (Rule of Three).\n   4. **Readability** — naming, function length, cognitive load, dead/commented code.\n   5. **Error handling** — validate at system boundaries; don't swallow exceptions; fail loudly.\n   6. **Security smells** — string-concatenated SQL/shell, secrets in code, missing authz, unsafe deserialization, user input reflected without escaping.\n   7. **Performance** — N+1 queries, unbounded loops, sync I/O in hot paths, unnecessary allocations.\n   8. **Testability & tests** — are new code paths covered? Are tests meaningful (see `write-tests`)?\n3. **Anti-patterns to flag** — magic numbers, deep nesting (>3), boolean parameters, primitive obsession, comments explaining *what* instead of *why*, TODOs without owner/ticket.\n4. **What NOT to comment on** — bikeshedding (formatter handles it), personal style preferences, hypothetical future requirements.\n5. **Output format** — group findings as `[blocker] / [should-fix] / [nit]` so the author knows what's actionable.\n6. **Checklist** — short bullet list to run through before approving / committing.\n\n## Verification\n\nAfter implementation:\n1. `ls .claude/skills/` — confirm both folders exist.\n2. `cat .claude/skills/write-tests/SKILL.md` and `cat .claude/skills/code-review/SKILL.md` — confirm valid YAML frontmatter (name, description) and well-formed markdown body.\n3. Restart Claude Code in this project (or run `/skills` if available) — both skills should appear in the available skills list with their descriptions.\n4. Smoke test: in a fresh session within this project, run `/write-tests` and `/code-review` and confirm each loads the skill content.\n5. The existing hooks under `.claude/hooks/` still fire (sensitive-file block remains active) — no settings.json changes were made.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- No language-specific examples (kept agnostic per user's choice).\n- No separate `security-review` skill (general review covers common smells per user's choice).\n- No CLAUDE.md created.\n- No changes to hooks, settings, or README.\n"},"tool_response":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/pauli/.claude/plans/please-show-me-the-sparkling-sky.md","content":"# Plan: Add project-level `write-tests` and `code-review` skills\n\n## Context\n\nThe repo is a Claude Code template at `/home/pauli/Downloads/ncd/workspace/claude-code-template`. It currently ships with hooks (sensitive-file blocking, history logging, notifications) but **no `.claude/skills/` directory and no `CLAUDE.md`**. There is no application code yet, so any \"best practice\" content must be language-agnostic to remain useful when the template is reused.\n\nThe user wants two project-level skills available to anyone who clones this template:\n\n1. **`write-tests`** — guidance for writing high-quality tests (industry-standard principles: AAA, FIRST, test pyramid, behavior-over-implementation).\n2. **`code-review`** — guidance for reviewing code before commit/PR (correctness, SOLID, readability, common security smells, scope discipline).\n\nBoth follow the standard Claude Code skill format: a folder under `.claude/skills/<name>/` containing a single `SKILL.md` with YAML frontmatter (`name`, `description`) and a markdown body. Naming avoids the user-level `review` skill already on this machine — using `code-review` prevents an accidental project-level override.\n\n## Files to create\n\n```\n.claude/skills/\n├── write-tests/\n│   └── SKILL.md\n└── code-review/\n    └── SKILL.md\n